oded and recoded as literary works find new homes on faraway bookshelves. Mani argues that the proliferation of world literature in a society is the function of a nation’s relationship with print culture—a Faustian pact with books. Moving from early Orientalist collections, to the Nazi magazine Weltliteratur, to the European Digital Library, Mani reveals the political foundations for a history of world literature that is at once a philosophical ideal, a process of exchange, a mode of reading, and a system of classification.Shifting current scholarship’s focus from the academic to the general reader, from the university to the public sphere, Recoding World Literature argues that world literature is culturally determined, historically conditioned, and politically charged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBooksxHistory. 0aBooks. 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literature. 0aLiterature and globalization. 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aBibliomigrancy.  aBook Series.  aEuropean Digital Library.  aHermann Hesse.  aJohann Wolfgang von Goethe.  aKarl Marx.  aNational Socialism.  aOrientalism.  aTranslation.  aWorld Literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823273430zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823273430423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823273430/original  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA1